<h1>Problem 1362 - 2021 IMO, P1 of 6, ACN</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 7</h2>
<p>Let \(n \geqslant 100\) be an integer. Ivan writes the numbers \(n, n+1, \ldots, 2 n\) each on different cards. He then shuffles these \(n+1\) cards, and divides them into two piles. Prove that at least one of the piles contains two cards such that the sum of their numbers is a perfect square.</p>
